   <mods:abstract>Since his return has spent most of his time in the country and has not
            written to friends in Europe. Mr. VaughanÆs family stopped by on their way to Albany
            with Sarah Livingston JayÆs sister (Catherine Livingston); everyone was in good health.
            Believes Mr. and Mrs. Vaughan would be more than happy to live in this country and leave
            England. Is more contented than he thought with the state of affairs at home; some
            things are wrong but more are right. There is public tranquility and private security.
            Resentments are dying down gradually; Whigs and Tories eat together at the same table.
            Tremendous industry in the country, good harvests and prices have fallen, although still
            elevated. The wages of mechanics and laborers are especially high, and house rents have
            more than doubled since before the war.</mods:abstract>
